            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              <div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Anyway, my point is, with Rhaegar dead, they have no purpose to be there - they'd actually be breaking their oaths by not being in King's Landing or Dragonstone, where Viserys &amp; Dany were - unless there was royal blood in that tower.</div><br />Yup.  I've re-read the conversation that Ned had with them at the tower, and it seemed rather clear that they felt they should be there.  Of course, that doesn't explain why they <span style="font-style: italic">weren't</span> in King's Landing previously, dying defending Aerys.  That oath about protecting the king is rather moot if the line of thought is &quot;well this king is screwed, let's leave him to die and go defend the next one!&quot;.  Plus, it still doesn't get around the idea that Jon is a bastard.  Rhaegar died before his wife Elia died, so he couldn't have married Lyanna, unless he also divorced Elia in secret.  With his trueborn heir (theoretically) killed in King's Landing, Viserys became king.

              

              
              
